\chapter{Parameters and Optimization}
\label{ch:parameters}



\lettrine[lines=2]{T}{he model} employs a three-tier parameter hierarchy comprising 114 parameters in total. This separation reflects a deliberate design decision grounded in the distinct roles that different parameter classes play in the simulation. At the highest level, 4 model parameters govern simulation infrastructure concerns such as spatial volume, grid resolution, random seed, and maximum step count; these are fixed by the modeler and do not vary across patient cases. The second tier consists of 18 patient parameters that encode clinical variables specific to each individual, including sex, BMI, treatment regimen, treatment start time, and 14 immune cell concentration measurements. These parameters are not subject to optimization because they are directly determined by clinical data from the ARON-1 dataset. The third and largest tier comprises 92 weight parameters that control the probability thresholds and scaling factors governing all biological processes in the model, from tumor cell proliferation and immune cell kill rates to glucose metabolism and drug effectiveness. These weight parameters are the target of Bayesian optimization, as they represent the biological quantities that cannot be directly measured from patient data and must instead be inferred by calibrating the model against observed clinical outcomes.

% ======================================================================
\section{Parameter Categories}
\label{sec:param-categories}

Parameters are organized into three dataclass objects: ModelParameters, PatientParameters, and WeightParameters.

ModelParameters: 4 simulation configuration parameters (volume, block size, random seed, max steps). PatientParameters: 18 patient-specific parameters (sex, BMI, treatment type, start time, plus 14 immune cell concentrations). WeightParameters: 92 biological process rate parameters optimized via Bayesian methods.

% ======================================================================
\section{Weight Parameters}
\label{sec:weight-params}

The 92 weight parameters control probability thresholds and scaling factors for all agent behaviors, organized by cell type. These parameters are optimized via Bayesian methods to match clinical trial outcomes. Table~\ref{tab:param-summary} provides a high-level overview; the complete per-parameter listings with defaults and descriptions are given in Appendix~\ref{ch:appendix-params}.

